flipped upside down.

227
00:12:57,150 --> 00:13:02,069
Suddenly, the condescending nobleman
is in awe of the merchant scum.

228
00:13:02,720 --> 00:13:06,670
That's what the art and the culture
does as a propagandistic tool.

229
00:13:07,210 --> 00:13:11,189
The next stage of it then is, "Okay,
we've raised these princes like this, and

230
00:13:11,190 --> 00:13:13,979
they have the Latin, and they have the
Greek, and they can impress everybody."

231
00:13:14,200 --> 00:13:19,470
Then they fight a bigger, nastier,
worse war than any of the earlier big,

232
00:13:19,480 --> 00:13:24,620
nasty wars, with more deaths and more
betrayals and bigger cannons knocking

233
00:13:24,620 --> 00:13:27,910
down cities and burning whole areas.

234
00:13:28,039 --> 00:13:32,790
The wealth is centralized, so
the mercenaries are more numerous

235
00:13:32,790 --> 00:13:35,050
because people can produce more.

236
00:13:35,240 --> 00:13:39,019
The first generations raised by this
are supposed to be philosopher princes,

237
00:13:39,020 --> 00:13:43,240
and instead we get Cesare and Lucrezia
Borgia, both of whom had Latin and Greek

238
00:13:43,240 --> 00:13:45,459
and Cicero and Plato when they were kids.

239
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:46,809
Then they grow up,

240
00:13:49,109 --> 00:13:51,410
and Cesare sets fire to half the world.

241
00:13:52,130 --> 00:13:54,440
That is the war Machiavelli watched.

242
00:13:55,520 --> 00:13:59,610
Machiavelli was raised on
all of the Cicero and Livy.

243
00:13:59,620 --> 00:14:01,315
He was raised on the Petrarchan project.

244
00:14:01,320 --> 00:14:05,010
He has this famous, beautiful letter
that he wrote in exile, where he's

245
00:14:05,010 --> 00:14:06,730
describing his day to his friend.

246
00:14:07,450 --> 00:14:12,440
Most of the day is wasted, and he
mucks around hunting for larks.

247
00:14:12,450 --> 00:14:17,160
Then he goes to a pub and gets drunk in
the company of uncultured countrymen.

248
00:14:18,550 --> 00:14:23,549
Then he goes home, and he gets dressed
in the court robes, the court finery

249
00:14:24,119 --> 00:14:28,330
that he would wear back when he was
an ambassador to popes and kings.

250
00:14:28,340 --> 00:14:34,059
Attired thus, he enters his library
to hold commerce with the ancients.

251
00:14:34,940 --> 00:14:38,189
He loves this the way Petrarch
wanted him to love it.

252
00:14:38,480 --> 00:14:43,346
But he observes these wars, and he
observes virtuous princes like Guidobaldo

253
00:14:43,346 --> 00:14:48,660
da Montefeltro, who does every single
thing you're supposed to do virtuously.

254
00:14:48,670 --> 00:14:51,540
He has all the Plato, and he has all
the libraries, and he has all the art.

255
00:14:51,990 --> 00:14:56,310
And he gets betrayed and his city taken
away from him and loses everything.

256
00:14:57,719 --> 00:15:01,709
And he watches terrible people
like Cesare Borgia and Julius II

257
00:15:01,920 --> 00:15:03,690
make terrible choices and succeed.

258
00:15:04,050 --> 00:15:09,490
He says, "Okay, clearly Petrarch was
wrong that just reading Cicero would

259
00:15:09,500 --> 00:15:12,790
make successful rulers like the Caesars.

260
00:15:13,240 --> 00:15:18,019
But I still feel in my heart
a deep power in the classics."

261
00:15:18,270 --> 00:15:23,030
So he says, "What if the libraries
are what we need, but we need

262
00:15:23,030 --> 00:15:24,060
to use them differently?"

263
00:15:24,590 --> 00:15:27,650
He proposes what we would
think of as political science.

264
00:15:27,650 --> 00:15:31,020
We observe historical examples.

265
00:15:31,080 --> 00:15:34,929
We say, "Okay, here are five examples
of battles that happened next to rivers.

266
00:15:35,260 --> 00:15:37,810
We'll put those examples side by
side and see what decisions the

267
00:15:37,810 --> 00:15:40,300
commanders made to try to figure
out which one worked better."

268
00:15:40,520 --> 00:15:44,890
We use history as a casebook of
examples of what worked and what didn't.

269
00:15:45,500 --> 00:15:48,580
We imitate what worked, and
we avoid doing what didn't.

270
00:15:48,740 --> 00:15:55,059
Instead of feeling that reading about good
men will make us good, we read about wise

271
00:15:55,059 --> 00:15:57,730
choices, and we imitate those choices.

272
00:15:58,030 --> 00:16:00,380
This is one of the reasons
Machiavelli is described by his

273
00:16:00,380 --> 00:16:02,500
contemporaries as a historian.

274
00:16:03,300 --> 00:16:06,430
He says we need to use history
and use the classics differently.

275
00:16:06,599 --> 00:16:07,790
He proposes that.

276
00:16:08,200 --> 00:16:10,010
He isn't very popular in his own day.

277
00:16:10,020 --> 00:16:11,719
It takes a long time for that to catch on.

278
00:16:11,730 --> 00:16:16,710
Many people for decades after him are
still trying to use absorption by osmosis.

279
00:16:17,040 --> 00:16:21,300
But he's writing that in the early
1500s, so it's been a little over

280
00:16:21,300 --> 00:16:22,800
a century since this started.

281
00:16:22,800 --> 00:16:25,740
We have to remember how
long this process is.

282
00:16:25,770 --> 00:16:31,570
From Petrarch's first call to Machiavelli
writing that is as long as from Yuri

283
00:16:31,670 --> 00:16:34,939
Gagarin's space flight back to Napoleon.

284
00:16:36,100 --> 00:16:40,870
The childhood of Napoleon to the space
race, that's Petrarch to Machiavelli.

285
00:16:40,880 --> 00:16:43,739
We think of it as one time
period, but a lot changed.

286
00:16:44,599 --> 00:16:45,599
They had a plan.

287
00:16:45,610 --> 00:16:46,810
They tried the plan.

288
00:16:47,240 --> 00:16:49,359
They brought the plan to its maximum.

289
00:16:49,360 --> 00:16:51,210
They raised all the
princes in this new way.

290
00:16:51,520 --> 00:16:52,380
The wars happened.

291
00:16:52,380 --> 00:16:53,470
It clearly failed.

292
00:16:53,670 --> 00:16:56,160
Machiavelli then thinks
about why it failed.

293
00:16:56,290 --> 00:16:58,090
We're still only halfway
through the Renaissance.

294
00:16:58,679 --> 00:17:01,340
Shakespeare's grandparents
have barely been born.

295
00:17:01,840 --> 00:17:03,199
We have a lot more time to go.

296
00:17:03,200 --> 00:17:04,499
So what do we need?

297
00:17:05,549 --> 00:17:07,050
We need new ways of thinking about it.

298
00:17:07,329 --> 00:17:09,690
We're reading the ancients,
and we have bigger libraries.

299
00:17:09,690 --> 00:17:11,679
We have the printing press now.

300
00:17:11,680 --> 00:17:13,520
We're having libraries in smaller towns.

301
00:17:13,520 --> 00:17:15,030
More and more people can read.

302
00:17:15,250 --> 00:17:17,129
It's easier and easier
to get an education.

303
00:17:17,139 --> 00:17:19,989
More people are starting
to learn about science.

304
00:17:20,679 --> 00:17:24,589
It also is important that they're
inventing micro technologies of

305
00:17:24,609 --> 00:17:29,220
book production like footnotes
and glossaries in the margin

306
00:17:29,220 --> 00:17:31,010
that explain the hard vocabulary.

307
00:17:31,900 --> 00:17:39,250
When Petrarch's successors like Ficino
were young, you had to be a masterful

308
00:17:39,360 --> 00:17:41,490
Latinist to read these ancients.

309
00:17:41,699 --> 00:17:43,050
You had to have an enormous vocabulary.

310
00:17:43,050 --> 00:17:44,140
There are no dictionaries.

311
00:17:44,140 --> 00:17:44,650
There are no glosses.

312
00:17:44,650 --> 00:17:45,990
There's nothing to help you.

313
00:17:46,270 --> 00:17:50,169
Only a tiny slice of expert classicists
could actually read this stuff.

314
00:17:50,740 --> 00:17:53,155
A hundred years later, there are
translations into the vernacular.

315
00:17:53,420 --> 00:17:55,380
There are footnotes that
tell you the hard vocabulary.

316
00:17:55,700 --> 00:18:02,129
Any med student can read Lucretius'
discussions of materialist information.

317
00:18:02,130 --> 00:18:05,930
When Poggio found it, there were two dozen
people in the world who could read it.

318
00:18:07,130 --> 00:18:12,809
A hundred years later, 30,000 people
can read it in the 30 print editions

319
00:18:12,870 --> 00:18:14,080
that are printed before 1600.

320
00:18:15,450 --> 00:18:21,690
When all different kinds of people read
it—med students, law students, people

321
00:18:21,690 --> 00:18:24,629
in different countries, people in
different places—they ask new questions.

322
00:18:25,560 --> 00:18:28,770
They wonder whether they
can test the hypotheses.

323
00:18:28,780 --> 00:18:29,590
They do test the hypotheses.

324
00:18:30,230 --> 00:18:33,269
They're the generation that
discovers that the heart is a pump.

325
00:18:34,119 --> 00:18:38,030
They're the generation that takes
seriously the question, "Maybe

326
00:18:38,030 --> 00:18:41,790
there are atoms, and maybe that's
how diseases work, and maybe we can

327
00:18:41,790 --> 00:18:43,350
develop the germ theory of disease."

328
00:18:43,380 --> 00:18:44,419
That's the 1560s, 1580s, 160

329
00:18:50,349 --> 00:18:55,019
years after Lucretius comes back,
because it takes generations of work

330
00:18:55,020 --> 00:18:59,910
to build the libraries, to have the
libraries, to use the libraries.

331
00:19:00,260 --> 00:19:05,340
So when we get to 1600, which is almost
exactly 200 years after this begins, a

332
00:19:05,340 --> 00:19:11,850
little bit more, we've had time to say,
"Let's build the libraries, have the

333
00:19:11,850 --> 00:19:15,870
libraries, use the libraries, or realize
we failed in how we use the libraries,

334
00:19:15,870 --> 00:19:17,470
and use the libraries differently."

335
00:19:18,170 --> 00:19:22,389
That's the generation of Francis
Bacon and Galileo who say, "Hey,

336
00:19:22,389 --> 00:19:24,050
let's use the information differently.

337
00:19:24,080 --> 00:19:28,229
Let's use nature as a casebook
of examples the way Machiavelli

338
00:19:28,240 --> 00:19:29,500
said we should use history.

339
00:19:29,869 --> 00:19:34,090
Let's examine, let's doubt, let's
rethink, let's do stuff in new ways."

340
00:19:36,380 --> 00:19:38,660
Just to make sure I understood,
the chain of causation here.

341
00:19:40,910 --> 00:19:44,559
We've got to resuscitate the virtues of
the Romans, therefore read what they read.

342
00:19:45,989 --> 00:19:47,659
To do that, you need
to build the libraries.

343
00:19:48,930 --> 00:19:51,060
You build the libraries, you
resuscitate all those arts.

344
00:19:52,060 --> 00:19:55,190
Then you just need to have people
be literate, have people think about

345
00:19:56,420 --> 00:19:58,640
information in a new way to analyze it.

346
00:19:58,910 --> 00:20:03,570
And that analysis lends itself not
just to the history of leaders, but

347
00:20:03,580 --> 00:20:05,810
also to the nature of the world.

348
00:20:07,590 --> 00:20:12,650
Whenever I hear a story about how
this is why the scientific revolution

349
00:20:12,650 --> 00:20:15,790
happened, why the Industrial Revolution
happened, I'm like, but there are so

350
00:20:15,790 --> 00:20:21,840
many stories and it's just hard to figure
out why this one over the other ones.

351
00:20:22,160 --> 00:20:24,382
There's a dozen other
stories you could tell.

352
00:20:24,382 --> 00:20:26,770
I had a previous guest, Joseph
Henrich, who has this theory that

353
00:20:27,090 --> 00:20:31,060
the Catholic Church was breaking
down these old kinship-based networks

354
00:20:31,060 --> 00:20:35,030
that the rest of the world had.

355
00:20:35,030 --> 00:20:38,080
It was encouraging guilds, encouraging
these kinds of centers where people

356
00:20:38,080 --> 00:20:39,410
could get together and discuss ideas.

357
00:20:41,200 --> 00:20:43,689
There are probably twenty
other stories you could tell.

358
00:20:44,209 --> 00:20:45,040
Why this story?

359
00:20:45,310 --> 00:20:47,050
Two different reasons.

360
00:20:47,280 --> 00:20:51,580
One, I think it's useful to think
about how for new ideas to flourish

361
00:20:51,580 --> 00:20:55,199
and new ways of running the world to
happen, you need a fertile environment.

362
00:20:55,210 --> 00:20:58,500
In the same way that for forests
to grow, you need enough topsoil.

363
00:20:58,510 --> 00:21:01,210
It takes a while to get that topsoil.

364
00:21:01,870 --> 00:21:03,760
It takes a while to get enough books.

365
00:21:05,130 --> 00:21:08,480
You need to have enough books for a bunch
of people to be reading and thinking.

366
00:21:08,490 --> 00:21:11,440
You also need to have networks of
information moving this stuff back

367
00:21:11,440 --> 00:21:13,899
and forth so that they can have
discourses of ideas with each other.

368
00:21:14,179 --> 00:21:16,690
You can't publish a scientific
journal until there are journals.

369
00:21:18,500 --> 00:21:23,010
You need to have developed this
ecosystem of information and knowledge.

370
00:21:24,250 --> 00:21:27,889
People talk about it sometimes in
terms of increasing literacy rates as

371
00:21:27,900 --> 00:21:32,019
if higher literacy makes there be more
books instead of the other way around.

372
00:21:33,069 --> 00:21:39,160
In fact, there's a lot more literacy than
people imagine in even medieval Italy.

373
00:21:40,970 --> 00:21:45,220
Florence had a male literacy
rate of ninety percent.

374
00:21:45,440 --> 00:21:46,840
As of the sixteenth century?

375
00:21:46,870 --> 00:21:48,439
As of the twelfth century.

376
00:21:49,599 --> 00:21:53,509
Because everybody's in the merchant world,
so you have to be able to send letters.

377
00:21:53,510 --> 00:21:55,300
You have to be able to read account books.

378
00:21:55,500 --> 00:21:58,300
You have to be able to calculate
your tab at a restaurant.

379
00:21:58,680 --> 00:22:00,979
But of those people, how
many have read a book?

380
00:22:01,000 --> 00:22:01,580
Very few.

381
00:22:02,250 --> 00:22:04,710
They've read letters, they've
read tallies, they've read

382
00:22:04,719 --> 00:22:06,540
indexes, they've made notes.

383
00:22:06,820 --> 00:22:11,949
The difference between being literate
and being book-literate is different.

384
00:22:12,820 --> 00:22:15,010
In the same way that some people
watch television but don't watch

385
00:22:15,060 --> 00:22:17,260
very many films, while other
people watch lots of films.

386
00:22:17,700 --> 00:22:22,020
You can be literate and have never
read a book because there might be

387
00:22:22,030 --> 00:22:27,979
almost no books in the entire city in
which you grew up if it's 1200 or 1500.

388
00:22:28,590 --> 00:22:33,120
But if it's 1600, there are definitely
books in any medium-sized town.

389
00:22:34,060 --> 00:22:41,170
So literacy transforms into access to
scientific, intellectual, legal, all

390
00:22:41,170 --> 00:22:43,520
sorts of different worlds of ideas.

391
00:22:44,660 --> 00:22:47,710
The other person you quoted who's
talking about transformations in

392
00:22:49,850 --> 00:22:53,660
networks of power from being less
family and clan-centered to being

393
00:22:53,870 --> 00:22:58,410
more guild-centered… The guilds are
major generators of ideas as well.

394
00:22:58,639 --> 00:23:00,670
The guilds can own libraries by 1600.

395
00:23:01,940 --> 00:23:05,160
If you went to a guild hall, it will have
a bunch of books about its own trade.

396
00:23:05,389 --> 00:23:07,250
That would not have been true in 1100.

397
00:23:08,380 --> 00:23:11,005
Those changes are all real,
they're all intermixing, and

398
00:23:11,040 --> 00:23:12,510
they're all parallel to each other.

399
00:23:13,090 --> 00:23:14,850
You need all of these things together.

400
00:23:15,740 --> 00:23:21,059
One of the focuses I have is
sometimes there are more steps

401
00:23:21,059 --> 00:23:22,999
to something than you think.

402
00:23:23,139 --> 00:23:26,300
We tell this story of the Renaissance,
of how they rediscovered these ancient

403
00:23:26,350 --> 00:23:28,060
texts, and then we got science.

404
00:23:28,200 --> 00:23:34,730
That's true, but it is an
oversimplification and too wide a zoom.

405
00:23:35,469 --> 00:23:41,269
If I said that in the French
Revolution, Napoleon rose to power

406
00:23:41,270 --> 00:23:45,780
and spread nationalized warfare
across Europe, and then we landed on

407
00:23:45,780 --> 00:23:48,350
the moon, I've skipped some steps.

408
00:23:50,750 --> 00:23:55,039
We know that about modernity, but we
don't remember that about earlier periods.

409
00:23:56,659 --> 00:24:01,830
Obviously all the stories are somewhat
true, but to the extent that this is a

410
00:24:01,840 --> 00:24:07,149
part of the story, you're building up
libraries of classics and … setting up

411
00:24:07,150 --> 00:24:10,560
a network of information exchange that
leads to the Scientific Revolution…

412
00:24:11,700 --> 00:24:16,770
The reason this feels salient right
now is that a lot of people have

413
00:24:16,770 --> 00:24:20,760
this idea that they're going to
make AI go well by doing X thing.

414
00:24:22,040 --> 00:24:24,170
Maybe some of those things work, but

415
00:24:26,610 --> 00:24:31,839
it's at the same time frustrating
but also funny and interesting that

416
00:24:31,860 --> 00:24:35,280
historically nobody has a good track
record of being able to say, "I

417
00:24:35,280 --> 00:24:41,389
will do this thing so that this huge
unanticipated change in history will

418
00:24:41,450 --> 00:24:43,360
go my way, or according to my values."

419
00:24:44,330 --> 00:24:44,830
Right.

420
00:24:44,929 --> 00:24:49,690
I think "go my way" as opposed to "go
well" is a really important distinction.

421
00:24:49,780 --> 00:24:50,280
Petrarch

422
00:24:54,020 --> 00:24:56,830
wanted a world with these values.

423
00:24:58,000 --> 00:25:01,130
He thought, for example, that this
would be a triumph for Christianity

424
00:25:01,130 --> 00:25:04,180
and what we would call Catholicism,
though there's only one Christianity

425
00:25:04,180 --> 00:25:07,090
from his point of view at the time,
except for the East, which is different.

426
00:25:09,330 --> 00:25:13,220
He was sure that when we found the
ancients, fundamentally all of their

427
00:25:13,220 --> 00:25:14,810
philosophy would agree with Christianity.

428
00:25:15,390 --> 00:25:20,250
The ancients were wise, therefore
they will be correct, and Plato will

429
00:25:20,250 --> 00:25:22,180
ninety percent agree with Christianity.

430
00:25:22,180 --> 00:25:26,349
It just needs a little shaker of the
Trinity on top to be Christianity.

431
00:25:27,330 --> 00:25:30,639
When he says, "Go find these
ancients," he is in a world that

432
00:25:30,640 --> 00:25:31,699
doesn't have the ancients yet.

433
00:25:37,830 --> 00:25:40,029
He's just guessing what's
going to be in these books.

434
00:25:40,550 --> 00:25:44,279
But he says, "If we find them,
they will uphold good values,"

435
00:25:44,280 --> 00:25:45,489
and everyone believes him.

436
00:25:46,389 --> 00:25:48,870
Then they go find them, and
they squabble with each other.

437
00:25:48,890 --> 00:25:52,540
There are Hedonists and Epicureans and
Stoics and all sorts of chaotic things,

438
00:25:52,540 --> 00:25:54,120
much more plural than he anticipated.

439
00:25:54,550 --> 00:25:58,810
It makes a world that in turn has giant
wars, which he would not like, and a

440
00:25:58,880 --> 00:26:03,739
crisis, and Machiavelli's critique of the
ancients, and then the new science and the

441
00:26:03,740 --> 00:26:07,340
new philosophy, and eventually Galileo,
none of which resembles what Petrarch

442
00:26:07,400 --> 00:26:10,450
imagined if he had specifically described
the future he was trying to make.

443
00:26:11,250 --> 00:26:17,530
But then we get to the propagators
of Bacon's scientific method,

444
00:26:17,540 --> 00:26:21,089
meaning Voltaire and Montesquieu,
who are also big campaigners for

445
00:26:21,089 --> 00:26:23,039
inoculation against smallpox.

446
00:26:23,049 --> 00:26:28,620
The first major disease eradications start
to begin under that immediate influence.

447
00:26:29,220 --> 00:26:32,139
Science gets us to the germ theory
of disease gets us to modern

448
00:26:32,139 --> 00:26:35,350
hygiene, which gets us to vaccines,
which gets us to penicillin and

449
00:26:35,910 --> 00:26:37,440
the treatment for the Black Death.

450
00:26:37,920 --> 00:26:41,190
Petrarch thought he would make
a world which shared his values.

451
00:26:41,219 --> 00:26:44,720
Instead, he made a world that
doesn't share his values but is

452
00:26:44,720 --> 00:26:48,340
capable of curing a disease he
never imagined would be curable.

453
00:26:49,230 --> 00:26:51,720
If you showed him this
future, it would be scary.

454
00:26:52,170 --> 00:26:54,790
It would be weird to him because
it does not embrace his values.

455
00:26:54,790 --> 00:26:55,780
Our values are different.

456
00:26:55,790 --> 00:26:57,539
He would be horrified by democracy.

457
00:26:57,540 --> 00:27:00,820
He believed that only a tiny
elite has the capacity to rule.

458
00:27:00,830 --> 00:27:02,429
If we had a time-traveling Petrarch,
he would really wrestle for a

459
00:27:02,430 --> 00:27:07,150
long time to wrap his head around
democracy as a functional system.

460
00:27:07,260 --> 00:27:09,370
He really thought in oligarchic terms.

461
00:27:10,340 --> 00:27:14,820
But he would see the wonders we've
created, especially the fact that

462
00:27:14,820 --> 00:27:18,980
we can treat the Black Death, and
he would weep for joy seeing that.

463
00:27:19,310 --> 00:27:23,962
He did not create a world
that went as he wanted, but he

464
00:27:23,962 --> 00:27:25,590
created a world that went well.

465
00:27:26,559 --> 00:27:28,069
We have many examples of that.

466
00:27:28,499 --> 00:27:34,460
Trains and bicycles come in, and
we get feminism because it's easier

467
00:27:34,460 --> 00:27:37,370
for people, especially women, to
move freely and independently.

468
00:27:37,370 --> 00:27:38,200
They can organize.

469
00:27:38,200 --> 00:27:39,050
They can mobilize.

470
00:27:39,050 --> 00:27:40,610
We get suffragettes.

471
00:27:40,620 --> 00:27:44,510
Did the inventor of the train intend
for there to be women's liberation?

472
00:27:45,309 --> 00:27:45,809
No.

473
00:27:46,000 --> 00:27:47,389
Did it go the way he imagined?

474
00:27:47,440 --> 00:27:47,820
No.

475
00:27:47,820 --> 00:27:49,009
Did it go well?

476
00:27:49,349 --> 00:27:49,849
Yes.

477
00:27:50,400 --> 00:27:50,900
It's

478
00:28:49,580 --> 00:28:53,730
important here to zoom in a little
bit on Florence's own government

479
00:28:53,730 --> 00:28:57,450
system and how and why it's weird,
in order to understand what rank

480
00:28:57,469 --> 00:28:59,019
Machiavelli actually holds in it.

481
00:29:01,000 --> 00:29:05,540
All of these republics, except
Florence, are modeled on ancient Rome.

482
00:29:05,779 --> 00:29:09,889
The ancient Roman model was an
oligarchic republic in which within

483
00:29:09,890 --> 00:29:13,950
the city there are certain noble
families, usually founding families

484
00:29:13,950 --> 00:29:18,760
who made the city in the first place,
who are the senatorial families.

485
00:29:19,139 --> 00:29:20,770
Hereditarily, when they come of
age, the men of the family are

486
00:29:20,770 --> 00:29:23,279
automatically in the senate.

487
00:29:24,000 --> 00:29:29,240
From among them are elected
the consuls, high senators,

488
00:29:29,240 --> 00:29:30,159
or the head of state if there

489
00:29:32,649 --> 00:29:32,720
is one.

490
00:29:32,720 --> 00:29:36,639
You have a small slice of the
population that are fully enfranchised

491
00:29:36,639 --> 00:29:40,689
members of the republic who
rule over the commoner majority.

492
00:29:41,010 --> 00:29:42,660
That is how Venice works.

493
00:29:42,910 --> 00:29:44,280
That is how Genoa works.

494
00:29:44,290 --> 00:29:46,650
That is how Bologna and
Siena for the most part work.

495
00:29:46,660 --> 00:29:48,200
That's how the Swiss Republic works.

496
00:29:48,210 --> 00:29:50,180
That's how all of these republics work.

497
00:29:51,620 --> 00:29:59,300
Florence was like that for quite a while,
but when republics fell, they usually fell

498
00:29:59,300 --> 00:30:05,040
to noble families who are the foremost,
the strongest, the military class.

499
00:30:05,050 --> 00:30:08,120
If you're a military leader in this
period, you have to have noble blood.

500
00:30:08,120 --> 00:30:10,879
No soldier is going to follow a
commander who doesn't have noble blood.

501
00:30:11,139 --> 00:30:12,299
That would be weird.

502
00:30:16,039 --> 00:30:19,890
Those threats to the independence
of the republic almost always

503
00:30:19,890 --> 00:30:20,970
came from the nobility.

504
00:30:21,360 --> 00:30:26,050
After one particular near miss
in which the city was nearly

505
00:30:26,050 --> 00:30:30,829
taken over, they decided to get
rid of the nobility of Florence.

506
00:30:31,049 --> 00:30:34,690
They massacred most of them, cut their
heads off, put them on pikes, burned

507
00:30:34,699 --> 00:30:37,820
their houses down, raked salt into the
earth, and had a party on their graves,

508
00:30:38,140 --> 00:30:41,070
the way you do in the period when
you're getting rid of a class of people.

509
00:30:41,340 --> 00:30:44,050
There were a few noble families
that they really liked who had

510
00:30:44,050 --> 00:30:45,460
not been part of negative stuff.

511
00:30:45,740 --> 00:30:49,120
They allowed them to officially
renounce their nobility.

512
00:30:49,160 --> 00:30:51,750
They renounced their nobility,
changed their names, and

513
00:30:51,750 --> 00:30:53,069
declared themselves commoners.

514
00:30:53,699 --> 00:30:55,500
They set up a commoner republic.

515
00:30:56,100 --> 00:30:59,770
What that meant was the senate
consisted of members of merchant guilds.

516
00:31:00,220 --> 00:31:04,929
A member of a merchant guild here
means the owners of workshops.

517
00:31:04,940 --> 00:31:08,180
It’s not the guy who sits at the
loom weaving, but the guy who

518
00:31:08,210 --> 00:31:11,139
owns the warehouse full of looms
where the workers are working.

519
00:31:11,559 --> 00:31:15,990
The head of the sculpture works,
the head of the architectural

520
00:31:15,990 --> 00:31:18,380
firm, not the bricklayers who
are actually laying the bricks.

521
00:31:18,390 --> 00:31:18,890
Bourgeoisie

522
00:31:21,570 --> 00:31:24,800
is an anachronistic word, but we're
talking about the owners of the means of

523
00:31:24,800 --> 00:31:28,360
production who are themselves commoners.

524
00:31:28,400 --> 00:31:32,330
They are very wealthy, but from
the point of view of the diplomatic

525
00:31:32,440 --> 00:31:38,140
corps of any other society, all of
the ruling people and all of their

526
00:31:38,140 --> 00:31:39,800
ambassadors are noble-blooded.

527
00:31:40,040 --> 00:31:42,399
If you're an ambassador, you're
automatically noble-blooded.

528
00:31:42,400 --> 00:31:44,750
Nobody's going to take an
ambassador seriously who isn't.

529
00:31:47,510 --> 00:31:51,389
From the perspective of every other
polity in the world, the rulers of

530
00:31:51,390 --> 00:31:53,070
Florence are the rank of their valet.

531
00:31:54,120 --> 00:31:56,260
There is no nobility left in the city.

532
00:31:56,260 --> 00:32:02,919
In fact, Florence can't run its own
armies or head its own police, because

533
00:32:03,150 --> 00:32:06,290
you're not going to surrender if you're
told to surrender in the name of some

534
00:32:06,290 --> 00:32:07,590
guy who doesn't have a coat of arms.

535
00:32:07,900 --> 00:32:08,930
That would be weird.

536
00:32:09,240 --> 00:32:13,760
So they actually have to hire a
nobleman to come to the city and be

537
00:32:13,760 --> 00:32:17,109
their chief of police to arrest people
in the name of the Holy Roman Emperor.

538
00:32:18,849 --> 00:32:22,700
One at a time, they'll invite
a skilled military commander

539
00:32:22,700 --> 00:32:24,020
nobleman who will come to the city.

540
00:32:24,020 --> 00:32:24,520
He'll be podestà.

541
00:32:25,020 --> 00:32:28,110
He'll live in the palace,
which is also the prison.

542
00:32:28,240 --> 00:32:29,190
He'll arrest people.

543
00:32:29,190 --> 00:32:30,430
He'll enforce the law.

544
00:32:31,180 --> 00:32:34,550
They will pay him handsomely at the end
of the year, escort him to the gates,

545
00:32:34,550 --> 00:32:38,129
and then banish him from the city for
life on pain of death so that he cannot

546
00:32:38,129 --> 00:32:42,760
return and make use of the power that
he had in the city to try to take over.

547
00:32:42,760 --> 00:32:45,949
They're very wary of any nobleman.

548
00:32:45,950 --> 00:32:49,910
They've set up a really weird
republic—weird from the perspective of

549
00:32:49,910 --> 00:32:54,359
everyone around them—in which a bunch
of merchants are trying to share power

550
00:32:54,650 --> 00:32:56,689
by being lotteried into the senate.

551
00:32:57,139 --> 00:32:58,889
You put names in a bag.

552
00:32:59,129 --> 00:33:01,669
You examine all of the
merchant members of guilds.

553
00:33:01,830 --> 00:33:07,040
You choose which ones are fit to
serve, meaning not ill and dying,

554
00:33:07,040 --> 00:33:10,979
not insane, not so deeply in debt
that they could be manipulated by

555
00:33:10,980 --> 00:33:12,800
the people whom they owe money to.

556
00:33:13,340 --> 00:33:14,320
Their names go in a bag.

557
00:33:14,320 --> 00:33:15,940
You choose nine guys at random.

558
00:33:16,219 --> 00:33:17,309
They rule the city.

559
00:33:18,089 --> 00:33:21,360
They are put in a palace where
they rule the city from that tower.

560
00:33:21,560 --> 00:33:24,760
They're actually locked in the tower
for the duration of their time in

561
00:33:24,760 --> 00:33:27,350
office because if they left the tower,
they could be bribed or kidnapped.

562
00:33:27,790 --> 00:33:30,590
They rule the city for
two or three months.

563
00:33:31,530 --> 00:33:34,174
At the end, they are thanked for
their service and escorted out, and

564
00:33:34,174 --> 00:33:37,909
then a different nine guys share
power for the next three months.

565
00:33:38,679 --> 00:33:41,810
It's a power sharing that is designed
to be tyrant-proof because you need

566
00:33:41,810 --> 00:33:48,169
consensus of nine randomly selected
guys to decide to do anything.

567
00:33:48,370 --> 00:33:49,690
Oh, it's not even a majority
vote, it's consensus?

568
00:33:49,719 --> 00:33:50,250
It's consensus.

569
00:33:53,350 --> 00:33:57,360
Previously you were describing
"kill the nobles, salt the earth".

570
00:33:57,710 --> 00:34:00,870
I'm almost thinking early communists.

571
00:34:00,870 --> 00:34:05,439
But then you say it's the heads of
the merchant guilds who are in charge.

572
00:34:05,440 --> 00:34:11,023
I want to understand why
merchants and entrepreneurs

573
00:34:11,250 --> 00:34:15,239
have notable status in Florence.

574
00:34:15,239 --> 00:34:17,550
What is it about the
culture that makes it so?

575
00:34:17,800 --> 00:34:21,279
Also, the Medici, the most powerful
people, their job is usury.

576
00:34:21,279 --> 00:34:21,366
It's like the church—

577
00:34:21,366 --> 00:34:23,990
It's important to remember they
were nobody when this set up.

578
00:34:26,000 --> 00:34:27,689
They were a minor important family.

579
00:34:27,689 --> 00:34:30,210
But the culture is getting started where
somebody like that could be respected.

580
00:34:30,489 --> 00:34:31,319
How does that happen?

581
00:34:32,199 --> 00:34:37,030
An important part of it is when you
have a merchant capital, everybody

582
00:34:37,040 --> 00:34:40,170
works for somebody who works for
somebody who works for the boss.

583
00:34:40,179 --> 00:34:46,829
If you are a major merchant in
Florence, you're importing and exporting

584
00:34:46,989 --> 00:34:48,799
wool to and from all across Europe.

585
00:34:49,029 --> 00:34:50,820
You have employees all across Europe.

586
00:34:50,820 --> 00:34:56,920
You're buying mass bulk wool from England,
importing it to Florence to use olive oil

587
00:34:57,179 --> 00:35:02,180
that you've bought from Naples to process
into high-quality wool, which you're

588
00:35:02,180 --> 00:35:04,020
then exporting to Germany and France.

589
00:35:04,320 --> 00:35:07,509
You are a very interconnected businessman.

590
00:35:07,510 --> 00:35:12,510
You have a lot of contacts, you have a lot
of clout, and the employees who work for

591
00:35:12,510 --> 00:35:18,170
you look to you for their safety net as
well as their political representation.

592
00:35:18,570 --> 00:35:22,779
We're very accustomed in the modern
period to thinking of the government

593
00:35:22,799 --> 00:35:24,359
as being our big safety net.

594
00:35:24,549 --> 00:35:28,803
If we wonder who is going to fund
the hospitals, whose job is it to

595
00:35:28,900 --> 00:35:32,980
take care of orphans, we think of
the government, or maybe the church.

596
00:35:33,290 --> 00:35:36,550
But in this period, if you're
killed and you leave orphans

597
00:35:36,550 --> 00:35:40,450
behind, it is your employer whose
duty it is to take care of them.

598
00:35:41,369 --> 00:35:45,440
If you are injured and can no longer
work, it is your employer who will

599
00:35:45,440 --> 00:35:48,900
support you for the rest of your life
while you are disabled and find you work

600
00:35:48,900 --> 00:35:50,610
that you can do with that disability.

601
00:35:50,950 --> 00:35:53,550
A huge portion of the
safety net is your employer.

602
00:35:53,770 --> 00:35:55,030
Are you in trouble with the law?

603
00:35:55,270 --> 00:35:57,979
Your employer will supply
your defense attorney.

604
00:35:58,670 --> 00:36:03,960
Your employer will supply the persuasive
note to the judge that they would very

605
00:36:04,010 --> 00:36:06,710
much appreciate if their person got off.

606
00:36:06,950 --> 00:36:10,510
This is the system known as the patronage
system, and it existed in ancient Rome.

607
00:36:10,510 --> 00:36:14,770
It exists and saturates the medieval and
the Renaissance worlds in which everyone

608
00:36:14,770 --> 00:36:17,050
is in a very interconnected hierarchy.

609
00:36:17,350 --> 00:36:23,460
So if you're a brewer and your son
gets in a barroom brawl and punches

610
00:36:23,460 --> 00:36:27,420
somebody out and the person's nose
breaks and they die in the brawl and

611
00:36:27,420 --> 00:36:30,199
your son is suddenly in trouble and you
say, "Oh no, I don't want my son to be

612
00:36:30,200 --> 00:36:33,600
executed," you turn to your landlord.

613
00:36:33,600 --> 00:36:35,810
Your landlord turns to his landlord.

614
00:36:37,070 --> 00:36:39,129
They turn to one of these major families.

615
00:36:39,230 --> 00:36:42,440
These major families are massive
landowners that own dozens of

616
00:36:42,480 --> 00:36:43,770
apartments within the city.

617
00:36:44,059 --> 00:36:46,230
Hundreds or thousands
of people work for them.

618
00:36:46,960 --> 00:36:51,340
So it makes sense to everyone to be
represented that way, like having

619
00:36:51,340 --> 00:36:54,970
a council of the CEOs of all of the
organizations that employees work

620
00:36:54,970 --> 00:36:59,610
for, when your corporation also
supplies your social safety net and

621
00:36:59,610 --> 00:37:01,110
you see your representation there.

622
00:37:01,880 --> 00:37:05,490
It's also a world that's used to thinking
in terms of hierarchy and very unused

623
00:37:05,509 --> 00:37:07,230
to thinking about real democracy.

624
00:37:07,389 --> 00:37:11,089
It really doesn't have any confidence
in what we would recognize as democracy.

625
00:37:11,359 --> 00:37:15,220
We talk about these republics, and
we're very excited by the fact that

626
00:37:15,220 --> 00:37:18,350
they give more power to the people
than a monarchy does, but they're still

627
00:37:18,350 --> 00:37:20,679
incredibly narrow oligarchic republics.

628
00:37:22,050 --> 00:37:25,300
When we read Machiavelli, he talks
a lot about the popolo, which

629
00:37:25,300 --> 00:37:26,530
we translate as "the people."

630
00:37:26,799 --> 00:37:31,920
He talks about how important it is that
the popolo are respected and have a

631
00:37:31,930 --> 00:37:36,529
voice, that the popolo are armed, and
the government shows respect for the

632
00:37:36,530 --> 00:37:38,230
people by allowing them to be armed.

633
00:37:38,530 --> 00:37:41,050
We read this and we're like,
"This feels really familiar.

634
00:37:41,050 --> 00:37:44,290
This feels like documents of the
founding of the US where we're respecting

635
00:37:44,290 --> 00:37:45,880
and arming and trusting the people."

636
00:37:46,190 --> 00:37:51,380
Popolo meant the top 4%
economically of the population,

637
00:37:51,390 --> 00:37:53,040
the members of the merchant guilds.

638
00:37:53,040 --> 00:37:54,100
That's the popolo.

639
00:37:54,510 --> 00:37:58,430
He's talking about a narrow-slice
oligarchy being heard, a narrow-slice

640
00:37:58,440 --> 00:37:59,879
oligarchy being respected.

641
00:38:00,290 --> 00:38:02,850
We didn't realize that in the
nineteenth century when we were

642
00:38:02,850 --> 00:38:07,049
excitedly translating The Prince
and reading it as quasi-democratic.

643
00:38:08,300 --> 00:38:11,190
We now have read more documents
of the period and realize

644
00:38:11,190 --> 00:38:12,440
how people use these words.

645
00:38:13,880 --> 00:38:18,210
Florence in this period goes through
five different forms of government.

646
00:38:18,860 --> 00:38:20,970
It's this republic of nine
dudes in a tower, as you were

647
00:38:20,970 --> 00:38:23,050
saying, before 1434, and then—

648
00:38:23,199 --> 00:38:25,209
There's a gradual takeover.

649
00:38:25,279 --> 00:38:28,299
There's a gradual, what we
could call regulatory capture.

650
00:38:28,470 --> 00:38:34,640
But an interesting detail about Florence,
even as the Medici take over, is that the

651
00:38:34,640 --> 00:38:38,720
Medici know the people of Florence are
very deeply invested in this republic and

652
00:38:38,780 --> 00:38:40,660
very deeply invested in its institutions.

653
00:38:40,660 --> 00:38:45,130
Therefore, they have to respect
those institutions and proclaim

654
00:38:45,130 --> 00:38:46,720
respect for those institutions.

655
00:38:47,160 --> 00:38:51,090
So they're going to sustain people in
the named offices that there used to be.

656
00:38:51,500 --> 00:38:55,490
They're going to continue to
let the guilds be important

657
00:38:55,530 --> 00:38:56,780
and have important offices.

658
00:38:56,799 --> 00:38:57,299
There

659
00:38:59,270 --> 00:39:04,549
was a mandatory outfit that people
wore who worked in the republic.

660
00:39:04,740 --> 00:39:09,820
The garment over there in the
corner is a lucco fiorentino.

661
00:39:09,860 --> 00:39:12,870
This was the garment you were
mandated by law to wear if you held

662
00:39:12,870 --> 00:39:14,149
office in the Florentine Republic.

663
00:39:14,549 --> 00:39:17,419
To us, we look at it and say, "It's
a long red robe. It looks very

664
00:39:17,420 --> 00:39:22,330
Renaissance." To them, it looked like a
toga because of the way it was draped.

665
00:39:22,340 --> 00:39:23,710
They thought of this as a toga.

666
00:39:24,000 --> 00:39:27,140
They're cosplaying the Roman Republic.

667
00:39:27,400 --> 00:39:32,229
Wearing a Florentine toga while
in office was something that you

668
00:39:32,230 --> 00:39:36,610
did to represent your fealty to
Cicero and republican values.

669
00:39:37,200 --> 00:39:40,370
The dukes made their men
continue to wear these.

670
00:39:40,390 --> 00:39:47,210
In fact, the first Duke, Cosimo I, would
wear one to costume balls as if in his

671
00:39:47,210 --> 00:39:52,470
heart he longed not to dress like a duke,
but to dress in a toga like a republican.

672
00:39:52,590 --> 00:39:57,760
It's doubly ironic because when the
Roman Republic turns to the Roman

673
00:39:57,760 --> 00:39:59,470
Empire, they still have the senate.

674
00:39:59,510 --> 00:40:02,350
They still have all these
old institutions, even though

675
00:40:02,350 --> 00:40:03,279
it's no longer a republic.

676
00:40:03,500 --> 00:40:07,049
The Roman Senate keeps
meeting until 1200 AD.

677
00:40:07,059 --> 00:40:12,549
It's sort of doubly ironic that they are
doing the same thing, but in the 1500s.

678
00:40:12,949 --> 00:40:17,640
And it means that more rights are
granted to the people of Florence

679
00:40:17,830 --> 00:40:21,379
than to other cities that fell
to monarchies at similar points.

680
00:40:22,120 --> 00:40:26,790
The monarchs of Florence know they
have to be careful, they have to

681
00:40:26,790 --> 00:40:30,420
respect rights to a certain amount,
and they can't run roughshod over them.

682
00:40:30,940 --> 00:40:34,810
There's a really cool building
that I love in Florence.

683
00:40:35,150 --> 00:40:38,450
If you've been there, there's the famous
bridge, the Ponte Vecchio, which has

684
00:40:38,470 --> 00:40:40,310
little jeweler shops all along it.

